## 7. Performance Comparison

### 7.1 Time Complexity

| Operation | Linked List | Red-Black Tree |
|-----------|-------------|----------------|
| Lookup | O(n) | O(log n) |
| Insert | O(1) | O(log n) |
| Delete | O(n) | O(log n) |

### 7.2 Real-World Scenario Analysis

```java
// Scenario 1: Normal hash distribution
Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
    map.put("key" + i, i);  // List length typically 0-2
}

// Scenario 2: Malicious hash collisions (DoS attack)
Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
String[] collisions = generateCollisions(10000);  // Same hash values
for (String key : collisions) {
    map.put(key, 1);  // JDK 1.7: O(n²) degradation
}                      // JDK 1.8: Converts to red-black tree, O(n log n)
```

### 7.3 Memory Usage

```
Node: 32 bytes (object header 12 + hash 4 + key 4 + value 4 + next 4 + padding 4)

TreeNode: 56 bytes
(Node 32 + parent 4 + left 4 + right 4 + prev 4 + red 1 + padding 3)
```

Red-black tree node memory usage is approximately **1.75x** that of a linked list node.

---

## 8. Best Practices

### 8.1 Set a Reasonable Initial Capacity

```java
// When the number of elements is known, avoid resizing
int expectedSize = 10000;
int capacity = (int) (expectedSize / 0.75) + 1;
Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>(capacity);
```

### 8.2 Implement a Good hashCode()

```java
// Bad hashCode: prone to collisions
class BadKey {
    int value;
    public int hashCode() { return value % 100; }  // Only 100 possible values
}

// Good hashCode: uniform distribution
class GoodKey {
    int value;
    public int hashCode() {
        return Integer.hashCode(value);  // 31 * value (standard implementation)
    }
}
```

### 8.3 Multi-Threaded Environments

```java
// Option 1: ConcurrentHashMap (recommended)
Map<K, V> map = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

// Option 2: Collections.synchronizedMap
Map<K, V> map = Collections.synchronizedMap(new HashMap<>());

// Option 3: Manual locking (not recommended)
Map<K, V> map = new HashMap<>();
synchronized(map) {
    map.put(key, value);
}
```

