## Binary Search

Binary search, also known as half-interval search, is a highly efficient search algorithm that works on sorted arrays.

In a sorted array, it eliminates half of the invalid range each time to quickly locate the target value.

- Time complexity: O(log n), far outperforming linear traversal for large datasets
- Prerequisite: The array must be pre-sorted in ascending or descending order

## Basic Search Principle

1. Set left pointer and right pointer
2. Take the middle position mid each time, compare the middle value with the target
3. If middle value is too small -> target is in the right half, move left pointer right
4. If middle value is too large -> target is in the left half, move right pointer left
5. If equal, found; if range is exhausted without match, the target doesn't exist

---

## Standard Implementation

```java
public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = arr.length - 1;

        while (left <= right) {
            // Calculate middle index
            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

            if (arr[mid] == target) {
                return mid; // Found target, return index
            } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
                left = mid + 1; // Target is in the right half
            } else {
                right = mid - 1; // Target is in the left half
            }
        }
        return -1; // Not found after traversal
    }
```

---

## Bit Operation Binary Search

> Bit operations are the most efficient
> Only supports ascending sorted arrays
> Can only return any matching index; cannot locate first/last position of duplicate elements

```java
public static int binarySearch(int[] a, int target) {
    // i: left boundary index, j: right boundary index, initially covering the entire array
    int i = 0, j = a.length - 1;

    // Closed interval search: i <= j means there are still elements in the range
    while (i <= j) {
        // Core: unsigned right shift by 1, equivalent to (i+j)/2, and won't overflow
        int m = (i + j) >>> 1;

        if (target < a[m]) {
            // Target is smaller than middle value, search left half, shrink right boundary
            j = m - 1;
        } else if (a[m] < target) {
            // Target is larger than middle value, search right half, shrink left boundary
            i = m + 1;
        } else {
            // Found target, return index directly
            return m;
        }
    }
    // Range exhausted, target not found
    return -1;
}
```

```java
public static int binarySearch(int[] a, int target) {
    // 1. Initial range: left-closed, right-open [0, a.length) -> covers entire array
    int i = 0, j = a.length;  

    // 2. Loop condition: i < j -> range is not empty (left-closed right-open, no elements when i==j)
    while (i < j) {  
        // 3. Unsigned right shift, prevent overflow, calculate middle index
        int m = (i + j) >>> 1;  

        if (target < a[m]) {		
            // 4. Target is in left half -> right boundary shrinks to m (right-open interval, no need to -1)
            j = m;  
        } else if (a[m] < target) {		
            // 5. Target is in right half -> left boundary shrinks to m+1 (left-closed interval, must +1)
            i = m + 1; 
        } else {
            // 6. Found target, return index
            return m; 
        }
    }
    // 7. Range is empty, target not found
    return -1; 
}
```

## Recursive Binary Search

> Prefer while iteration in production code

```java
private static int search(int[] a, int i, int j, int target) {
    // Recursive termination: range is empty, not found
    if (i >= j) return -1;

    int m = (i + j) >>> 1;
    if (target < a[m]) {
        return search(a, i, m, target);   // Recurse into left range
    } else if (a[m] < target) {
        return search(a, m + 1, j, target); // Recurse into right range
    } else {
        return m; // Found target
    }
}
```

## Left Boundary Binary Search

> Array has duplicate values, returns the first index equal to the target

```java
public static int leftBoundary(int[] a, int target) {
    int i = 0, j = a.length;
    while (i < j) {
        int m = (i + j) >>> 1;
        if (target < a[m]) {
            j = m;
        } else if (a[m] < target) {
            i = m + 1;
        } else {
            // Core: don't return when found, keep searching left!
            j = m; 
        }
    }
    // Final i == j is the left boundary
    return i < a.length && a[i] == target ? i : -1;
}
```

## Right Boundary Binary Search

> Array has duplicate values, returns the last index equal to the target

```java
public static int rightBoundary(int[] a, int target) {
    int i = 0, j = a.length;
    while (i < j) {
        int m = (i + j) >>> 1;
        if (target < a[m]) {
            j = m;
        } else if (a[m] < target) {
            i = m + 1;
        } else {
            // Core: don't return when found, keep searching right!
            i = m + 1; 
        }
    }
    // Final i-1 is the right boundary
    return i > 0 && a[i - 1] == target ? i - 1 : -1;
}
```

The core logic of all implementations is identical; only the range shrinking rules differ slightly.

